Austin Bluffs, Pulpit Rock, and University Park open space areas make up the 585.5 acre Austin Bluffs Open Space area. There are trails throughout the area, but the most developed trails are near Pulpit Rock. Trailheads are located off Rockhurst Boulevard and N. Nevada Avenue. It is considered "unique" by the United States Forest Service for its unusual sandstone rock formations.
The 37.4 acre area provides access to Foothills Trail and has a historic stone bridge.
S. Powers Boulevard and Bradley Road
Walking trails along the 646.9 acre open space provide views of the Front Range and the Big Johnson Reservoir.
South of Fillmore, East of Mesa Road
The Mesa Valley Trail may be accessed from the 11 acre open space.
Walking trails cross the 22.3 acre property.

The open space, with important paleontological and archaeological resources, is not yet open to the public. Guided tours are available at the park. The Corral Bluffs Alliance (CoBA) works to preserve the park and its resources.
The area is 22.4 acres and provides access to the Sinton Trail.

The 54.6 acre open space has parking near the trailhead on south side of Stetson Hills Boulevard. The terrain is mixed grass prairie and has scrub oak. The highest point in Colorado Springs is the crest of the ridge in this open space.
South of Fillmore Street, East of Mesa Road
The open space covers 41.8 acres. Trails provide access to the Mesa Valley trailhead.
There is a total of 172.7 acres with open space tracts in the North Gate development area.
South of Garden of the Gods Road and N. Nevada Avenue
3615 W. High Street, off of Highway 24

13.8 miles of developed trails for hiking and horse-back riding are found in the 784.9 acre open space. There is also a dog off-leash trail and picnic area. Parking is off of Ore Mill Road and 31st Street, including a horse trailer area, and the main parking area is off of Ridge Road and Highway 24.
Tammarron Drive and Saddle Mountain Road
Sinton Road between Fillmore Street and Garden of the Gods Road
A wetlands area is located within the 13.1 acre open space.
The 99.5 acre open space amenities include trails which connect to the Mesa Valley Trail, the Beidleman Environmental Center, picnic area and restrooms. The area is wheelchair accessible.
There are 17.2 acres in this open space.

There are "hiking only" and multi-use trails, which allow for horse-back riding, hiking and biking. There are two trailheads, Le Veta Way trailhead west of Cresta Road (21st Street) and Ridgeway Avenue, north of W. Cheyenne Boulevard. A restroom is located at the La Veta trailhead and there is parking at both trailheads. There are 318.3 acres in this open space.
The 78 acre property has a gravel path.
N. Union Boulevard, between Austin Bluffs Parkway and N. Academy Boulevard

Acacia Park, the city's first park, is located at Bijou and Tejon Streets, adjacent to the Palmer High School. The park is enjoyed by high school students at lunchtime and in the summer children enjoy the Uncle Wilber Fountain. Visitors also inlcude people who work downtown, shoppers and other visitors. The park has a band shell.
There are 2 baseball and soccer fields on the 6.4 acre park.

Antlers Park, situated on 3.4 acres, includes a sidewalk path, picnic area, and reservation picnic shelter amenities. The park is handicapped accessible. It has a historic locomotive exhibit.(For citations, see Adams Park, a neighborhood park.)
The 3 acre park has a soccer field, sidewalk path, and picnic area.(For citations, see Adams Park, a neighborhood park.)

A picnic area and shelter, band shell and sidewalk path are located in the 1.2 acre path. The park is handicapped accessible and has restroom facilities.(For citations, see Adams Park, a neighborhood park.)
Within the 7.1 acre park is a playground, picnic shelter and sand volleyball court.(For citations, see Adams Park, a neighborhood park.)

Sports facilities are available in the 3.3 acre park for baseball, softball, basketball, soccer, football and a multi-play half-court. There are also playground and picnic areas and a sidewalk path.(For citations, see Adams Park, a neighborhood park.)

There are 2 fields for baseball or softball, 2 fields for soccer or football and 2 tennis courts in the park. There is also a picnic shelter, playground, sidewalk path and restrooms. The park is handicap accessible. It is 8 acres in size.(For citations, see Adams Park, a neighborhood park.)
The 3.9 acre park includes a multi-play court, 2 tennis courts and a basketball court. There is also a picnic shelter and playground.(For citations, see Adams Park, a neighborhood park.)

There are fields for softball or baseball and football or soccer, a multi-play court and 2 tennis courts, with practice boards. Within the 7.2 acre park are also a picnic area, playground, sidewalk path and restrooms.(For citations, see Adams Park, a neighborhood park.)
There is a picnic table and historic plaque in the small park.(For citations, see Adams Park, a neighborhood park.)

table-1281-231.caption: Living Legends
data: Former Deputy Surgeon General of the United States. First dean of Uniformed Services University Graduate School of Nursing. Authored Patient Centered Approaches to Nursing.

Founding president of National Association of Hispanic Nurses. First Hispanic nurse to complete PhD at New York University. First Hispanic nursing school dean at New York University. Recipient of Hildegard Peplau Lifetime Achievement Award.
Author of Interpersonal Relations in Nursing. Only person to hold president and executive director posts at American Nurses Association.
Former assistant surgeon general of the United States Public Health Service. Recipient of Distinguished Service Medal from USPHS. Involved in creation of the 1964 Nurse Training Act.
Dean emeritus at University of Washington School of Nursing. Former president of the American Academy of Nursing. Namesake for an aging center at University of Washington.

Department head for public health nursing at University of Illinois College of Nursing between 1970 and 1980. Helped to establish the master's degree in public health nursing at the school. Served as an international nursing consultant and received an order of knighthood from the Emperor of Japan.

Dean emerita of the Frances Payne Bolton School of Nursing at Case Western Reserve University. Established faculty and nursing practice collaborations at the school. Served on a task force to create the 1964 Nurse Training Act.

Chair of pediatric nursing at University of Maryland. Established a research program at the university hospital's neonatal intensive care unit. Developed a "rocking hammock" and studied stimulation in premature infants. Created a conceptual model for maternal-child nursing.
Founding dean of the University of Florida College of Nursing. Developed the clinical assessment database. Served as a hospital chief of nursing practice while on the faculty at Florida.
Former president of the American Nurses Association. Headed the USPHS Division of Nursing. Advocated college education for all nurses.
Founded the nursing school at Auburn.
First female interim president in the Ivy League.
Emeritus professor and transcultural nursing expert.
Co-created the first pediatric nurse practitioner program at Colorado.
Former executive director of the International Council of Nurses.
President of Texas Woman's University between 1986 and 1993.
Pioneered clinical research in cardiovascular nursing.
Presidential adviser on mental health and aging.
Editor of Nursing Outlook. Past president of Sigma Theta Tau International. Created interdisciplinary nursing administration program at Columbia.
Founded the first U.S. birthing center.
Established the first American hospice team.
Editor of Textbook of Medical and Surgical Nursing and Lippincott Manual of Nursing Practice.
Early leader in the nursing informatics movement.
Developer of the concept of continuing nursing education.
Early nurse anesthetist. Namesake for a professional advocacy award given by the American Association of Nurse Anesthetists.
Editor of Nursing Research from 1979 to 1997. Directed early graduate programs in nursing.
Editorial staff member of Nursing Outlook, Nursing Research and American Journal of Nursing. Developed the Contemporary Nursing Series.
Introduced the theory of goal attainment.
Director emerita of the Barbara Bates Center for the Study of the History of Nursing.
Nurse theorist who studied infant mental health.
Author of Reality Shock: Why Nurses Leave Nursing.
Former president of Sigma Theta Tau International and the American Academy of Nursing. Author of The Growth and Development of Mothers and The Growth and Development of Nurse Leaders.
Established a faculty practice system at Pittsburgh's School of Nursing.
Former dean at UCLA. Cardiovascular researcher who wrote 110 peer-reviewed articles.
Hospital chief nursing officer. One of the four authors of Magnet Hospitals: Attraction and Retention of Professional Nurses.
Dean emerita of UIC College of Nursing. Co-editor for several editions of Current Issues in Nursing.
Creator of the theory of health as expanding consciousness.
Retired associate director and former director of the Center for Nursing Historical Inquiry.
Longtime nursing journal editor. Author of Sunflowers in the Sand: Stories from Children of War.
Former dean at Duke. Developed the first clinical master's program in nursing.
Former dean at Yale School of Nursing. Created first graduate entry program in nursing.
Created the Feetham Family Functioning Survey.
Co-director, Gerontological Nursing Interventions Research Center
President, Friends of the National Institute for Nursing Research. Former president of Sigma Theta Tau International.
Professor emerita at the University of California San Francisco.

Juliette is revealed to constantly be called on the phone by her mother, who is a drug addict and wants money to feed her drug needs. Juliette records three songs Rayna turned down for her album. Rayna eventually wants them back but it's too late.
